600–Female":"1600–Deceased","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1597":"1597","about 1600":"about 1600","1651":"1651","1617":"1617","1703":"1703","Hull, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hull, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chapman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a merchant or trader, Middle English <i>chap(pe)man</i>, <i>chepman</i>, Old English <i>cēapmann</i>, <i>cēpemann</i>, a compound of <i>cēap</i> ‘barter, bargain, price, property’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’.","Jewish: adopted probably for a like-sounding or like-meaning name in some other European language; see for example   Kaufman  .","History: This name was brought independently to North America from England by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. John Chapmen (sic) was one of the free planters who assented to the ‘Fundamental Agreement’ of the New Haven Colony on June 4, 1639."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatman","meanings":["English: altered form of   Chapman  ."]},{"name":"Kaufman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Chaim, Emanuel, Moshe, Eytan, Herschel, Zvi, Ari, Aron.","Americanized form of German   Kaufmann  , and a variant of the same Jewish surname.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Kaufman</i> meaning ‘merchant’. Compare   Koyfman   2."]},{"name":"Chipman","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>chipman</i> (Old English <i>cȳp(e)mann</i>), a side form of <i>chapman</i>, <i>chepman</i> ‘merchant, trader’; see   Chapman  , with which this name was interchangeable."]},{"name":"Copeman","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): patronymic from the early Middle English personal name <i>Cop(e)man</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Scandinavian <i>Kaupmaðr</i>. It is a transferred use of Old Scandinavian <i>kaupmaðr</i> (Old Danish <i>køpman</i>) ‘merchant’, cognate with Old English <i>cēapmann</i> (see   Chapman  ), but there is no evidence for the occupational term in Middle English.","Americanized form of North German   Koopmann   or Dutch   Koopman  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":0,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":20,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705213,"age":42,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert John Chapman was born about 1600, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert John Chapman."},"et":{"about 1600–":"umbes 1600–Surnud","1597–Male":"1597–Surnud","1617–1703":"1617–1703","1600–Female":"1600–Surnud","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1597":"1597","about 1600":"umbes 1600","1651":"1651","1617":"1617","1703":"1703","Hull, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hull, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1600–":"noin 1600–Kuollut","1597–Male":"1597–Kuollut","1617–1703":"1617–1703","1600–Female":"1600–Kuollut","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1597":"1597","about 1600":"noin 1600","1651":